In an effort to curb this trend, some states, including California, have implemented provisional driver's licenses that restrict the hours and passengers for teen drivers. However, I believe these measures are merely a temporary fix. The core issue lies in the fact that, statistically speaking, the youngest drivers are not equipped to handle the risks and responsibilities associated with driving. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman's research suggests that 18 is still too early for a full driver's license, as those under 19-20 tend to be thrill-seekers. Delaying driving licenses until this impulse subsides could save countless lives. Continuing to issue licenses to young teens will only lead to more tragic accidents and a staggering death toll in the coming years, particularly when millions of new teen drivers hit the road by 2010, the year the Baby Boomers' children become eligible.

Implementing legislation to address this issue would be a relatively straightforward process. Schools could continue to offer driver's education classes to lay the groundwork for future drivers, but no one under 18 should be allowed to operate a vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued before granting a full license, and a set number of practical training hours could be required. This number could be based on the existing standards of most states, such as California's 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult. Uniform national legislation would be a reasonable and effective way to protect teenagers across the country. This idea is not a new one, but it's a sound solution to a pressing problem.

I decided to dive into the Library of Congress's treasure trove of early Edison films, specifically the trick films from 1895 to 1901. There are 15 of them in total, and I found myself captivated by their creative use of editing to conjure illusions. My exploration of these films focused on analyzing the poetic elements that make them tick and identifying the progressive characteristics that set some of the later films apart. At the turn of the century, trick films were largely static, confined to a single, frontal proscenium, and adhered to a strict one-shot-per-film rule, with a focus on long and medium shots. However, a few early 20th-century films dared to break free from these conventions by incorporating multiple shots.

One thing that stood out to me was the common thread of filming within an interior set, framed within a frontal proscenium. The camera remained stationary, refusing to follow figures or objects as they moved. This composition drew its roots from the theatre and, for trick films, the world of vaudeville and magic shows. A limitation of this setup was that figures in trick films were generally confined to side-to-side movement, unable to approach or recede from the camera. Take, for instance, the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), where the actors enter from the right and move back and forth along the horizontal axis, disappearing from view without the camera following them.

The frontal proscenium style also led to a reliance on long shots, with medium shots appearing less frequently. Close-ups were nonexistent in these early trick films, a nod to the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would witness the entire performance from a fixed vantage point. As in many early films, actors rarely moved towards the camera, making close-ups a rarity. Most trick films from the Edison catalog stuck to the rule of one conceptual shot per film, keeping their length brief – typically under a minute, depending on the frames per second used. This constraint limited the dramatic and narrative potential of these films, which often focused on short, vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearances, and switching acts with minimal storytelling. However, a closer examination of these films revealed that what appears to be one physical shot can, in fact, be several joined together to create the illusion of apparition or disappearance, as seen in The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), where a more detailed inspection reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, even though the entire film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

Meet John Taylor of Caroline, a true pioneer in the realm of Republicanism. As a passionate advocate for individual liberties and limited government, his unwavering dedication to these causes was forged in the fires of his agricultural pursuits and brief foray into politics. While his work as a farmer formed the foundation of his views on governance, it was his conviction in the superiority of agrarian life that colored his opinions on sovereignty, constitutionalism, and the judiciary.

Taylor believed that the United States possessed a unique opportunity to craft an ideal system of government, untainted by the influence of native traditions. This blank slate allowed him to envision a system of self-governance that would safeguard the inherent rights of individuals, which he believed were interdependent and indivisible. If one right was compromised, the value of all others would suffer. Consequently, these rights should be beyond the reach of government meddling. In his view, the so-called "state of nature" was a chaotic realm where the strong preyed on the weak, but he believed that civilization should not perpetuate this paradigm.

To create an ideal society, Taylor posited that a government must be established that acknowledges the duality of human nature – its propensity for both good and evil. He was resolute in his adherence to a dualistic morality, arguing that government, being an extension of humanity, would reflect both its virtues and vices. Taylor defined good principles as those that protected private property, promoted agriculture, and discouraged excessive capitalism. He contended that a government grounded in these principles would function impartially, despite the inevitable presence of self-interest and avarice in its administration. However, he believed that self-interest was only malevolent when it led to the proliferation of sub-societies that exploited others at the expense of the greater good. A benevolent government was necessary to contain humanity's darker tendencies, and it must be vigilantly monitored to prevent the introduction of pernicious principles.

Like many stalwart Republicans of his time, Taylor championed a strict construction of the Constitution, advocating for a minimalist federal government with only the powers explicitly granted to it. He recognized that an expansive federal government was prone to despotism due to its associated costs. However, Taylor cautioned against a literal interpretation of the Constitution, warning that it could lead to corruption without consideration for the intent of its authors. Moreover, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, as it more explicitly described the country as a federation of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

Looking back at the data in Figure 17, we noticed a significant drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. This was a bit of a letdown, and it's tough to pinpoint the reason behind it. One possibility is that the onset of winter on our New England campus led people to abandon their bikes and foot-powered commutes, which could account for part of the decline. The end of the fall semester in December might also have played a role, as students and faculty were preoccupied with finishing schoolwork, processing grades, and the like, making it easy to overlook the commuter log. The start of the holiday season in December, followed by a month-long break for students and faculty, likely contributed to the low number of submissions. Things picked up again when classes resumed in late January, but the low numbers persisted through February. It's possible that the initial enthusiasm for the project wore off, leading to a natural decline in engagement. To counter this trend, we launched the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special blitz campaign to revitalize the initiative, which succeeded in boosting log submissions for that month. However, this still left us grappling with the challenge of maintaining momentum despite the inevitable decrease in engagement due to holiday and semester breaks. Another hurdle for our project, and for any alternative commuting initiative, is the deep-seated cultural attachment to driving one's own vehicle. To overcome this, it's essential to offer incentives that appeal to people's love of freedom, independence, and flexibility on the road. We rewarded participants with gift cards to local eateries, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local bookstore, and even larger chain stores. It would have been interesting to see how bigger prizes might have impacted participation – perhaps a shiny new bike, a hybrid car, or an electric vehicle. This could have helped mitigate the dip in engagement we experienced. The prizes remained the same throughout the project, but if we had announced additional incentives over time, like a bike in December and a car in January, engagement might have increased instead of decreased.

Imagine a financial product that's a hybrid of an index fund and a stock, offering the benefits of diversification and flexibility. That's what an exchange-traded fund, or ETF, is all about. Unlike a traditional mutual fund, an ETF allows you to buy and sell it on an exchange, much like a stock, but with the added advantage of tracking an index or a basket of assets. The allure of ETFs lies in their ability to provide diversification, the benefits of single stock ownership, and the flexibility to sell short, buy on margin, or purchase a single share in any transaction. But don't let that fool you - the expense ratios of ETFs are often lower than those of the average mutual fund. However, there's a catch: you'll need to pay a commission on every trade, just like you would with a stock order.

The real beauty of ETFs lies in their vast array of options, with various funds catering to different investment needs. But, it's crucial to keep in mind that even with these benefits, it's essential to scrutinize the actual performance of the ETF and its components. In this case, we're taking a closer look at the ETF IHF and its top 10 holdings, which account for a significant 63.58% of its assets. By examining these top holdings, we'll determine whether owning a single ETF can provide similar benefits to diversifying your portfolio with the same stocks.

To keep things concise, we'll focus on the top 10 holdings, representing the bulk of the ETF's assets. We'll use this subset to estimate how well the ETF's 10 stocks represent the entire fund. By calculating the Beta and return of a portfolio comprising only these 10 stocks, in the same proportions as the ETF's holdings, we can gauge their performance. The results are telling: a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings shows a 6.11% higher return, a whopping 16% increase, compared to the ETF. Moreover, the Beta of this portfolio is a full 0.12 lower than the ETF's, suggesting a potentially more stable investment.

However, it's essential to note that these findings might not be statistically significant. To confirm, we'll examine the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks, normalized to 100%, and compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

I have always been fascinated by Edgar Allan Poe's magnum opus, "Dream-Land." This enchanting poem is, in Poe's own words, one of his best works. One of the most intriguing aspects of "Dream-Land" is Poe's repeated use of the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56. According to the esteemed scholar Mabbott, this enigmatic reference can be traced back to the great Roman poet Virgil. Virgil, in his turn, borrowed the term from an ancient Greek concept, describing Thulé as an island situated at the edge of the known world, situated north of Britain.

However, there's more to the story than meets the eye. Poe's fondness for German literature is well-documented, and it's likely that he drew inspiration from the works of the celebrated German author Goethe. Karl J. Arndt, in his seminal work "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," highlights the striking similarities between their two poems, concluding that Poe was, in fact, influenced by Goethe's writing.

The connection between Poe and Goethe is further cemented by Goethe's iconic poetic drama, "Faust," which was published in two parts, with the first installment appearing in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year of Goethe's passing. Within the second part of "Faust," there's a poignant poem titled "The King of Thulé." This haunting tale revolves around a king whose wife gives him a goblet before her passing, only to see him succumb to excessive drinking and despair. The king's eventual decision to give his possessions to his children and throw the goblet into the ocean, symbolizing his desire to join his beloved wife in death, bears an eerie resemblance to the demeanor of the speaker in "Dream-Land." It's almost as if Poe's work is a dark mirror reflection of Goethe's, echoing his own struggles with loss and addiction.

Poe's use of the term "Thulé" is more than just a coincidence, as he references it twice in his collected writings, including "The Pit and the Pendulum" and "Dream-Land." In fact, the two poems can be seen as companion pieces, with "The King of Thulé" serving as a haunting precursor to the desolate landscape of "Dream-Land." The speaker's description of Thulé as a dark, lonely, and colorless world, haunted by the ghosts of departed friends, bears an uncanny resemblance to the king's own emotional state after the loss of his wife. This shared atmosphere of despair and longing suggests a deep connection between the two poems.

It's worth noting that Poe's admiration for Goethe was not limited to his own work. He also spoke highly of the English poet Tennyson, which would have introduced him to Goethe's writing. Moreover, the numerous reproductions of Goethe's work that followed its original publication would have ensured that Poe was well-versed in his literary legacy.

You might wonder if a customer who slipped on a mess of applesauce at a grocery store and got hurt would be able to get punitive damages from the store manager, who ignored the spill for half an hour because he was too busy eating dinner. The manager had been informed twice about the spill, and even after that, he didn't do anything about it. But will a judge throw out the customer's claim right off the bat? 

I'd bet not. To get punitive damages, the customer will have to prove that the store manager acted with a reckless disregard for the harm that would come from leaving the spill there. They'll also have to show that the store manager's actions were despicable - basically, really bad and intentional. The customer has a good shot at this, considering that several other customers had slipped and fallen in the months before and the manager still did nothing to fix the problem. 

Here's the background: on October 13th at 5 pm, an employee told the manager, Paul Martin, about the applesauce spill, and he just blew him off, saying he was on his dinner break. Fifteen minutes later, another employee reminded him about the spill, and he gave the same response. Just half an hour later, the customer, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill and hurt her back. It turns out that this wasn't an isolated incident - five other customers had slipped and fallen at the store that same year. Now Palmer is suing the store for both compensation and punitive damages.

In California, a customer can sue for punitive damages if the store acted with malice - basically, if they intended to hurt the customer or showed a "despicable" disregard for the customer's safety. The law defines malice as acting with intent to harm or acting with a reckless disregard for others' safety, even if there's no intent to harm. It's like the court said in a previous case, when the defendant was aware of the potential danger of their actions and still chose to ignore it.

It's been nearly four years since I took a course in Islam at CBC, a journey that sowed the seeds of a long-standing question: is Islam a hostile religion? As I reflect on the past two decades, I'm struck by the pendulum swing in public perception, oscillating wildly between hostility and excessive tolerance. The aftermath of 9/11 marked a turning point, as mass media shifted from a predominantly negative view of Islam to a more accepting stance. I find it astonishing that in 2001, it would have been unimaginable to have a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, whose family ties to Islam are undeniable.

The biography of the Prophet Muhammad has long fascinated me, particularly the contradictions between history and the narrative's portrayal of his personality. In my understanding, Muhammad was supposed to be a forceful figure who coerced people into converting to Islam, conquering tribes and imposing his faith upon them. However, the biography presents a different picture – that of a humbled and misunderstood prophet, who humbled himself before others, and his message drew people to him one by one as they discovered the 'truth'. This dichotomy leaves me intrigued and, to a certain extent, perplexed.

A striking parallel exists between the ministries of Jesus and the reported miracles of Muhammad. One notable example is the multiplication of mutton and milk, which was more than enough for forty men. This style of writing makes me believe that the authors aimed to depict Muhammad as a humble prophet, not one driven to prove himself, but one who lived in truth and miracle. This narrative strategy concerns me, as it diminishes the life and message of Jesus Christ, seemingly appropriating and diluting his significance. It's as if they're borrowing from and attempting to claim Jesus' legacy for Muhammad.

Furthermore, the biography attributes great importance to providing evidence of 'witness' and how people 'independently' converted to Islam. However, many stories rely on hearsay, often tracing back to a third-party source. I found this approach off-putting, as it diminishes the stories' authenticity and makes them seem all the more suspicious.

What bothers me most about this work is the attempt to elevate Muhammad to a godly figure, emphasizing his humility, gentle nature, and wisdom. Yet, historical accounts contradict this portrayal, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true circumstances surrounding Muhammad's rise to power.

It's fascinating to note that the core teachings of Jesus have largely been left in the dust as Christianity evolved over the centuries.  If we look at the broader timeline, it's clear that Christianity has gradually strayed further and further from its original roots.  Today, we're witnessing a growing awareness of this trend and an unprecedented desire for progress.  While traditionalists will undoubtedly resist any attempts to move beyond established dogma, their influence may ultimately be outweighed by those craving a deeper understanding of the faith's true origins.  As the years go by, historical awareness will become increasingly widespread among Christians, sparking a yearning to distinguish the doctrines that have been added to the faith from the intentions of its namesake.  This shift may take decades or even centuries, but the end result is inevitable:  Christianity will undergo a great reversal, progressing backward toward its original form.  A movement will gain momentum, shedding layer upon layer of doctrine as if time itself were rewinding, until all that remains is a glimpse of what Jesus brought to humanity on behalf of God, untainted by the interpretations of subsequent thinkers.  As this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, it will draw in the masses, influencing them to worship in a more authentic, Jesus-centric way.  The institutional church will remain strong, guiding the faithful on this journey back to the faith's roots.  However, this reverse trajectory will bring about a surprising consequence: instead of the rich diversity that has characterized Christendom, we can expect to see a growing uniformity of belief and practice across regions, denominations, and divisions.  History is replete with examples of this kind of reversal, such as how the Roman Empire, once a persecutor of Christians, eventually became a bastion of the faith.  Similarly, our country has transitioned from a time of African-American slavery to a era of African-American leadership.  The impending reversion in Christianity will be a remarkable process, undoing centuries of accumulated tradition in search of the original source, and in the process, erasing the very diversity that has come to define the faith.  Crucially, this transformation will be facilitated by a more nuanced approach to Jesus' words, viewing them as metaphors rather than literal statements.  So, what exactly happened since Jesus' time?
       Looking further back into history, we find that the roots of Christianity lay firmly in Judaism.  By the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., the core tenets of the faith were already in place: monotheism, a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures.  However, the Jewish population was far from unified, with various factions like the Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and common people vying for influence.

The Jungle is an expose that reveals the darker side of human nature - a side where self-interest and greed reign supreme. Beneath the surface, we find individuals consumed by a never-ending pursuit of personal gain, with little regard for anyone or anything else. This is starkly evident in the portrayal of the factory owners and managers, who prioritize profit over people and the environment. As Upton Sinclair vividly illustrates, their relentless drive for growth and expansion leaves a trail of destruction in its wake, as seen in the image of "the line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair's depiction of the pollution and neglect is a scathing indictment of the owners' callous disregard for those affected by their actions.

The factory owners and managers also demonstrate a lack of concern for their employees, whom they treat as mere commodities to be exploited for their labor. They stop at nothing to maximize profits, regardless of the cost to the workers' well-being, as evident in the statement "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." The employees are subjected to grueling working hours, with little notice or support when they are laid off, often leaving them to fend for themselves in a system with few regulations to protect their rights. The book portrays a system where workers are expected to sacrifice their health and dignity for the sake of their jobs, with no safety net or support to fall back on.

The era in which The Jungle is set saw a lack of laws and regulations to safeguard workers' rights, allowing the factory owners and managers to operate with impunity. The unions that formed to represent the workers often ended up perpetuating the exploitation, profiting from the very people they were supposed to protect. As a result, the workers were trapped in a cycle of poverty and dependence, with little hope of escape. Sinclair's stark conclusion is that, in this system, immorality and desperation are inevitable, much like under the institution of slavery.

The art of crafting a narrative that evokes a certain mood or attitude in readers is a delicate dance that many authors attempt to master. Not all of these techniques are equally effective, and F. Scott Fitzgerald's novel The Great Gatsby is a prime example of this. To create a lasting impression, Fitzgerald frequently employs a range of literary devices, including juxtaposing words that don't typically go together. He also assigns deeper meanings to symbols, which he then cleverly incorporates into his writing. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald expertly uses colors, like white/gray and red/pink, to build an aura around important subjects.

One of the most striking aspects of Fitzgerald's use of color is the way he imbues white/gray with a sense of uniformity. To him, white connotes elegance and refinement, while gray represents something more aged and worn. He sets the stage for this association early on in the novel by consistently using these colors. For instance, Daisy and Jordan are often depicted wearing white, as are most other characters. Nick sports white flannels at Gatsby's party, Tom wears a white shirt when meeting Myrtle, and Catherine is described as "powdered milky white." Conversely, when Nick describes Gatsby's party, the atmosphere is described as "gaudy with primary colors," implying that white is typically reserved for more subdued settings. Fitzgerald reinforces this association by applying these colors to everyday objects and people, such as the "white chasms of lower New York" Nick navigates every day, or the "gray names" on Nick's schedule.

Fitzgerald also uses white and gray to describe common, unremarkable people and places. For example, he describes Jordan and Daisy's shared "white girlhood," the "gray cars" and "gray land" in the valley of ashes, and the "gray old man" selling dogs. By applying these colors to the mundane, Fitzgerald creates a sense of sameness, highlighting the monotony of everyday life.

After establishing the meaning of white/gray, Fitzgerald uses them to convey a sense of unimportance or uniformity, particularly in relation to Daisy. After a pause in their use, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in a "little white roadster," subtly suggesting that she has become a uniform, almost interchangeable part of Gatsby's world. This technique is repeated when Daisy is described as wearing a "gray haze of fur collar" and a "white" dress before her encounter with Tom and Gatsby. Through this use of color, Fitzgerald skillfully conveys Daisy's status as a desirable object, rather than a fully fleshed-out character.

The land of San Diego County is a haven for agricultural bounty, thanks to its pleasant climate and an abundance of sunshine. Crops like tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, and peppers thrive in the area. With a strong demand for organic, community-supported agriculture, local farms have long waiting lists. Even organic eggs and milk are in high demand. Many of these farms open their gates to visitors, offering behind-the-scenes tours and opportunities for hiking, birdwatching, and other leisure activities. This type of operation not only allows landowners to tap into government incentives but also enables them to create a haven for wildlife, promoting biodiversity and offering a chance for educational programs and revenue streams.

While organic farming can be a lucrative venture, it also has its own set of challenges. For one, it requires more labor and management to keep pests and weeds at bay without relying on chemicals, and losses can be greater than those experienced by conventional methods. Additionally, small organic farms often can't match the efficiency of larger operations, and practices like planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, and invasive species removal can be labor-intensive and costly. Considering these factors, a landowner in this scenario might seek financial assistance or expert guidance to optimize both profits and habitat quality.

The land in question is a 160-acre property in unincorporated San Diego County, adjacent to the town of Potrero. It's a diverse landscape of chaparral, nonnative grassland, and oak woodland, bordering the Cleveland National Forest. This area falls within the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan, which currently considers over a hundred species of plants and animals, many of which are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the California gnatcatcher, while others are declining and may soon be listed.

For centuries, Native Americans inhabited this land before it was settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This particular piece of land was part of an original homestead patent, likely used for grazing and wood production for many years.

To explore the possibilities for a small farmer on this land, I selected a real estate listing and researched government programs that could help mitigate costs and preserve wildlife-friendly practices. As a model of what someone farming this land might aim to achieve, I chose an organic farm in the same region.

The impact of culture on negotiations cannot be overstated. Culture is a multifaceted entity that is often misunderstood or oversimplified. We frequently hear generalizations like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating," but these broad statements do little to illuminate the complexities of cultural attitudes. A more nuanced understanding of a culture can be gained by recognizing what it signifies and what it is not. In other words, culture is just as much about its absence as its presence.

When approaching a foreign culture, we inevitably make comparisons to our own, which can lead to a superficial understanding. To truly grasp a culture, one must delve deeper, studying its history, understanding its prejudices, and acknowledging its idiosyncrasies. Rather than judging or trying to change a culture, it's essential to accept it for what it is and work within its boundaries, especially in the high-stakes world of negotiation.

The boundaries of culture extend far beyond national or international borders. Corporate cultures can be just as distinct as national cultures, with their own values, norms, and expectations. A company's dress code, communication style, and hiring practices can all reveal its underlying culture. For instance, some companies prioritize long hours in the office, while others encourage a more relaxed schedule. Even within a single company, regional and urban-suburban differences can create diverse subcultures.

To succeed in negotiation, it's crucial to understand the underlying values of a culture. If, for example, saving face or communal harmony is deeply ingrained in a culture, a negotiator will likely avoid public shaming or confrontation. Conversely, a culture that values a hard-driving bargain may not prioritize settling for a quick agreement. By considering these generalities before the negotiation table, a savvy negotiator can adapt their approach and build a stronger relationship with their opponent.

Moreover, taking the time to learn about an opponent's personal values and motivations can be a game-changer in effective negotiation. By doing so, a negotiator can tailor their approach to the unique cultural context and create a more harmonious and productive discussion.

I often wonder, 'What's the point of even arguing?' As the saying goes, "The fool hath said in his heart, 'There is no God.'" A phrase famously coined in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and later echoed in the writings of St. Anselm. This particular concept seems to be shared by the equally influential Thomas Aquinas, and as we delve into their works, it's clear that their arguments are intertwined. For the sake of simplicity, let's assume both authors believe in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. This allows us to focus on their arguments without getting bogged down in nuances. 

As we explore their views, I'd like to suggest that while both St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas present compelling points, their approaches leave room for improvement. Let's start with Anselm's take. He posits that understanding God begins within ourselves. According to him, we can't fathom a world without God, so we must accept that God exists because it's inherent to our understanding. Anselm's idea is that our minds are the ultimate authority for determining the truth about God, and that external evidence is unnecessary. This concept is at the heart of Christian faith – a leap of trust without concrete proof.

In stark contrast, Thomas Aquinas takes a more empirical approach. He believes that God's existence can be proven through reason and evidence, freeing Christians from the need for faith. This would be a game-changer for evangelism, allowing converts to be wooed by logic rather than blind faith. Aquinas presents five distinct logical arguments for the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each of these demonstrates that the necessity of God is a logical inevitability, akin to understanding a missing puzzle piece by piecing together the rest of the puzzle.

It all began sometime in the 5th or 6th century BCE with a prince destined to become the revered Buddha. Over the course of his life, he turned his back on worldly pursuits and discovered enlightenment. His teachings eventually gave rise to Buddhism – a 2,500-year-old tradition that has undergone significant transformations since its inception. This evolution can be observed in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is a poignant example. Despite the fact that Buddha never taught about such festivities, monks and lay followers alike participate in this ritual, making it a crucial aspect of their spiritual lives. This divergence from the original teachings is just one of the many ways in which Theravada Buddhism has adapted its theological and philosophical foundations over time. These changes have been influenced by both internal and external forces – some benevolent, others malevolent.

Throughout this discussion, we will frequently use various terms to describe these forces. 'Internal' refers to influences stemming from within the Buddhist community, regardless of one's monastic status. External influences come from outside the community. A hostile force is any element that seeks to harm or damage the Buddhist community, often stemming from a negative perception of Buddhism. In contrast, a benign force has no intention to harm or assist the community, although it may inadvertently have one of these effects.

Let's start by examining the fundamental principles of Theravada Buddhism – the core doctrines that have guided the community for centuries. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is comprised of the Tripitaka – the three baskets of sacred texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka outlines the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka delves into the metaphysical aspects of Buddhism. These notions include the concepts of Anatta – the absence of a permanent self, Dukkha – the inherent suffering in life, and Anicca – the impermanence of everything. By acknowledging these fundamental truths, one can break free from Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, and ultimately eliminate lobha – desire, dosa – hatred, and moha – delusion. The Vinaya Pitaka outlines the rules for lay followers, such as the five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not engage in misconduct, and I shall not consume intoxicating substances). Monks, on the other hand, adhere to a more extensive set of disciplinary rules. The four noble truths form the foundation of Buddhist doctrine: the first, that life is suffering; the second, that attachment is the root cause of suffering; and the third, that suffering can be overcome.

It's hard to believe how the United States and Mexico were once locked in a 57-year rivalry that lasted from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The rivalry reached its peak with the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the US came out on top, claiming Texas and the American Southwest as its own territory. This wasn't an isolated incident – there were many other clashes between the two nations before the First World War finally brought an end to the hostilities. 

This long-standing rivalry was fueled by deep-seated differences between Americans and Mexicans on issues like faith, culture, and tradition (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31). Sound familiar? This isn't a unique scenario – neighboring nations often clash over competing interests, leading to enduring rivalries. The US and Mexico are just one example of a pair of nations that, despite sharing a border, struggled to see eye-to-eye. David M. Pletcher (1977) noted that Mexico and Cuba are the only Latin American nations that have presented long-term diplomatic challenges for the US (p. 41). It's no coincidence that they're both geographically close to the US and have a history of rivalry.

Religious differences were a major point of contention between the two nations, a problem that has plagued many countries throughout history. As Sally Frahm (2001) pointed out, "if Americans opposed fascism and communism in the 20th century, they were once opposed to Catholicism and monarchy in the 18th and 19th centuries" (p. 86). This ideological struggle was as much about competing interests as it was about differing values. In this case, the ideological differences were rooted in the religious preferences of the two nations, a legacy of the distrust between the English and Spanish empires. This inherited animosity made it difficult for the US and Mexico to establish a positive relationship.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) documented 17 disputes between Mexico and the US during the 57-year rivalry period. Most of these disputes centered on territorial issues, including border raids from Mexican territory and other frontier problems. Border violence, particularly from American border towns, was a persistent issue until the US and Mexico finally exerted military force to control their borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97).

As Schmitt (1974) noted, the rivalry began to subside as Mexico became increasingly dependent on the US (p. 109) and American ambitions shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico (p. 110) in the late 19th century. This marked the end of the long-standing rivalry between the two nations.

It was 15 years ago that an unexpected illness suddenly rendered me unable to work. At the time, I was a nurse, a profession I had chosen for the security and stability it promised, a sense of safety I desperately craved as a child. The mantra that echoed through my adolescence and beyond was "you'll always find work; people will always get sick." So, I put aside my dream of becoming a scientist or journalist to pursue a more practical path.

Now, at 46, I'm single, broke, and living on the fragile support of Social Security Disability. Fifteen years have passed, and I've lost everything that truly belongs to me. Each day is a struggle, a relentless assault on my sense of security, safety, and self-worth. The only constant in my life is the unwavering support of my family and a few loyal friends, who've been my lifeline in times of crisis.

Despite my strength, I've come to realize that when disaster strikes, it's a cruel illusion to think you can face it alone. Life's emergencies, whether big or small, are a guarantee. No amount of preparation can shield you from the overwhelming forces that life throws at you.

I agree that our reliance on the government is a fragile foundation, but I firmly believe it's time for Americans to rediscover the value of trust, community, and mutual aid. Rather than building individual shelters, we should be learning to support one another, to ask for help when needed, and to offer a helping hand in times of need.

The concept of rugged individualism, touted by Conservatives as the backbone of American spirit, is a myth. Our forefathers didn't survive the harsh realities of frontier life alone; they thrived on compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains knew that working together was the only way to reach their destination.

So, by all means, prepare for the unexpected. I've stocked my disaster kit with essentials, from first aid supplies to water purification tablets and duct tape. I've got flashlights, batteries, candles, and canned goods, ready for any eventuality. But while you're at it, take a step further – get to know your neighbors.

By building connections and fostering a sense of community, we can create a safety net that's stronger than any government program or emergency kit. It's time to rediscover the values that truly made America great: compassion, mutual respect, and a willingness to help one another in times of need.

I've always wondered, what drives organisms to evolve the way they do? Are there hidden rules, constraints that shape the path of evolutionary change? The field has been puzzling over this question for a long time, and even Darwin's contemporary, D'Arcy Thompson, noted in 1917 that scientists were still struggling to quantify the simplest forms of life. Fast-forward to today, and while we've made progress, we still have a long way to go. Recently, some scientists have applied mathematical modeling to the way mollusks grow their shells, looking at both how they develop over time (ontogeny) and how they've changed over millions of years (phylogeny). Our study is taking a similar approach, using math and experiments to figure out what drives the twists and turns of evolutionary change in a group of snails called Prunum.

We started by studying X-ray images of Prunum shells to identify key characteristics that could help us model how their shells might change over time. These characteristics were then plugged into a software program called CerioShell, which let us simulate different shell shapes and sizes. By comparing these hypothetical shells to real ones, we're hoping to get a better understanding of how Prunum shells have evolved over time.

Shells are like a spiral staircase, growing outward in a continuous loop. Each turn of the shell is called a whorl, and they're connected by a line called a suture. The largest whorl is the last one, called the body whorl, and the tip of the shell is the apex. As the shell grows, the animal extends out through an opening called the aperture. By looking at shells from different angles – apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural – we can get a better sense of their shape and size.

To count the number of whorls, you need to look at the shell from the top and find the first suture. Then, draw a line and start counting from there, estimating to a quarter of a whorl if necessary. By mapping out the path of the aperture through time and space, we can see how the shell has grown and changed over time. This journey can be represented mathematically and graphically, allowing us to experiment with different parameters and see how they affect the shell's development.

By combining math and experiments, we're one step closer to understanding the mysteries of evolutionary change in Prunum.

For the past decade, Indonesia has witnessed a stagnation in neonatal and infant mortality rates.  While the country is making progress in achieving some of the Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets, the rate of improvement in child and maternal health has fallen woefully short of the required target by 2015.  The multitude of factors behind this lag will be discussed below, suggesting a need to fortify the health system rather than focusing on programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has seen an increase in the number of births attended by skilled healthcare workers, with 72% now meeting this benchmark.  However, this statistic also includes traditional attendants like midwives who cannot provide medical assistance in complicated cases, thus contributing to the high rate of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage.  Consequently, the improvements in this indicator are somewhat misleading, and there is still much work to be done.  Moreover, there has been a decline in the percentage of children under five treated by a healthcare professional for diarrheal cases.  The data on postnatal care is incomplete, but it is evident that this area is a concern, with low rates across the country.

The rate of cesarean sections remains alarmingly low at around 4%, and another red flag is raised by the fact that these rates are 7% in urban settings, but only 2% in rural areas.  This disparity highlights the issue of unequal access to healthcare services across the country, with urban areas receiving more attention.  The problem of vertical equity is also apparent, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles, indicating that the poor are struggling to access healthcare services due to high out-of-pocket costs.

When considering the next steps towards improving neonatal and maternal care indicators, the most fundamental question is how to effectively address the shortage of services.  Specifically, should Indonesia opt for program-specific approaches or strengthen its overall health system without focusing solely on pre and post-pregnancy care for mothers and children?  While programmatic approaches to address the problems outlined may seem attractive, they have drawbacks.  For instance, heavily investing in a single area can divert resources away from other critical sectors, leading to a brain drain of human resources towards the more funded area.  Furthermore, running multiple parallel programs can result in duplication of services, uncoordinated efforts, and an increase in paperwork and administrative burdens.

Victorian novels are often characterized by their meticulous attention to detail, frequently focusing on the aristocracy of the era.  However, two notable exceptions are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, which stray from this tradition by incorporating elements of mystery and the bizarre, characteristics not typically associated with Victorian fiction. These elements add depth to the characters within each novel, providing insight into their motivations and emotions.

The narrative of Oliver Twist is riddled with bewildering and confusing ideas as the protagonist navigates the dark world he inhabits. He finds himself caught between the turbulent lives of Sikes and Crackit, who are locked in a heated dispute. The words they exchange echo in his mind, making it difficult for him to distinguish reality from fantasy. In a state of disorientation, he's suddenly jolted back to reality by the sound of gunfire, and the world around him descends into chaos. A sense of unease and pain lingers, haunting him as he's whisked away by an unseen force. This passage from Dickens' work illustrates the unsettling nature of Oliver's world, where he's often overwhelmed by the harsh realities that surround him.

Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights employ the use of dream sequences or dreamlike states to convey the mystery within their narratives. In Oliver Twist, these strange occurrences often reveal Oliver's inner turmoil, offering a glimpse into his deepest pains and fears. When the shooting incident is revisited in chapter 28, Oliver relives the moment vividly, as if stuck in a dream, while desperately searching for help. This passage underscores the lack of control Oliver has over the events unfolding around him, highlighting his dire situation and the trauma he's endured. As he's overwhelmed by the memory of the shooting, the question arises as to whose will is at play, suggesting that Oliver's misfortune may not be his own doing. This reinforces the idea that he's at the mercy of forces beyond his control, leaving him feeling defeated and powerless to act.

Similarly, Wuthering Heights is marked by long, oppressive nights that stretch on forever, yet seem to pass by in an instant. The day is always fleeting, and the silence is oppressive, making the hours feel like an eternity. This sense of timelessness is a fitting backdrop for the turmoil that unfolds within the novel.

A couple of years ago, I was working with an after-school program where I tutored elementary-age students in various subjects. I did my best to help them in the areas where they were struggling, but my strengths lay in English and reading. One student, a young boy named Adrian, really caught my attention – he was in third or fourth grade, I think. He had a peculiar problem with reading, which only became apparent as I worked with him. Some letters were no-brainers for him, while others left him stumped, which was bizarre. Given his likely Latino background, I was taken aback by his perfect English skills, but it all started to make sense when I met his mother.

The moment she walked in, speaking only Spanish, it hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian's literacy issues weren't about reading itself, but the English alphabet and its pronunciation. I realize now that my limited Spanish skills at the time made communication a bit of a challenge, but we managed to convey our message. That epiphany led me to wonder if that revelation ever helped him in the long run, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier issue in schools, particularly in California, and to show that it's not always as straightforward as we think. Even for kids who speak perfect English, reading can be a significant hurdle. I believe everyone acknowledges this problem, so what's the solution? In Adrian's case, it was as simple as targeted English reading tutoring, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for kids who barely speak English, it's a much more complex issue. There's no one-size-fits-all answer. We can't rely on any single method – dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutors, or ESL classes – to solve this problem. The key lies in combining multiple approaches.

One thing that stands out is the dual language system, which is an excellent idea not just for kids who speak Spanish as their first language but for all students. Research shows that children in two-way bilingual education programs outperform their peers academically. A lot of misconceptions surround this idea, claiming it's a waste of resources and that most students won't benefit. But that's a false assumption. If we implemented these programs as the norm, rather than the exception, all children would benefit from them. So, how do we make it happen? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? That's unrealistic and unreasonable. Instead, I think we can have bilingual aids, tutors, or whatever we want to call them, to support students in the classroom.

We've all been conditioned from a young age that there's something greater than ourselves, something that transcends our understanding. Some of us are raised in Sunday school, while others explore their spirituality through meditation or introspection. Many of us stick to the faith passed down to us by our parents, but some reject it altogether, opting instead for a more personalized worldview. We navigate a complex landscape of spirituality, searching for our own unique answers to the mysteries of the universe. Our quest for meaning often begins with a desire to escape the darkness and find solace in the light.

One rainy evening, I recall sitting on the porch with my father, watching the gutters overflow with rainwater, drowning the plants at the edge of the step. He stared out into the downpour, a look that was both distant and introspective. His health had taken a turn for the worse, and his once robust physique had given way to a more gaunt appearance. His hair had thinned, and his eyes seemed to be searching for something beyond the present moment. I felt a deep sense of unease and longing, but the words caught in my throat, unable to articulate the depth of my sorrow. I hugged him, sat back down beside him, and joined him in gazing out into the rain-soaked twilight, the sound of the raindrops a melancholy serenade.

My father passed away in December, just five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation had prolonged his life, but at what cost, I couldn't help but wonder. What kind of higher power would allow this suffering? In the dead of night, I found myself praying not to a deity, but to an empty void, as if pleading for an answer that never came. If there was a God, I thought, he had long since stopped listening to my pleas.

I couldn't bring myself to witness my father's final moments. I chose to remember him by his life, not his passing. I knew him better than anyone else, and I knew he wouldn't have wanted me to be a spectator to his death. For three days, I curled up in my bed, waiting for the news that would change everything. But the silence was deafening – no one called to share the news with me.

I've always found it fascinating how the term "Gothic Novel" seems to be an oxymoron - an "old-new" hybrid, as Ian Watt puts it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. For years, the Gothic mode has been both maligned and lauded, with some arguing it lacks depth and others praising its "terrible sublime" qualities (Burke). I suspect this duality stems from the genre's roots in a bygone era. The original "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, cleverly combined elements from both "ancient" and "modern" romances to birth the proto-Gothic genre. By blending the old with the new, Walpole created a new form of literary expression. The Gothic genre drew inspiration from medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions, yet it was often seen as old-fashioned and unsophisticated in comparison to the "modern" literary and societal advancements of its time.

One of the defining characteristics of Gothic novels is the idea of chivalry, a medieval concept that emphasizes the virtues of a proper knight. This notion, as seen in The Castle of Otranto, is not only retained but also transformed. Chivalry, particularly in the context of the Gothic novel, represents an idealized and romanticized version of the past - a time when knights were brave, honorable, and competent. This nostalgic portrayal hints at the future evolution of Gothic into Romantic literature. Walpole, who wrote The Castle of Otranto during a tumultuous period, may have been attempting to critique the present by idealizing the past. His character Frederic, for instance, embodies many chivalric traits - he's a prince, a victim of tragedy, and a gallant and courteous figure. This exaggerated portrayal of the "gallant and courteous Knight" sets the stage for the Gothic trope of excess.

As I sit here, pondering the intricacies of the business world, I find myself reflecting on the concept of supply chain management - that intricate dance of moving goods from customer orders to raw materials, supply, production, and distribution, all the way to the customer's doorstep. It's a process that has been around since 1982, when consultant Keith Oliver coined the term. Oliver described the elaborate process of planning, implementing, and controlling the supply chain to satisfy customers' needs in a swift and efficient manner. The puzzle pieces of supply chain management revolve around six key elements: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information.

A manager's best friend in this supply chain game is the production stage, the foundation upon which the entire process stands. It's the moment when the 'when, why, where, and how' of production is outlined. To get to this point, managers must tap into the market, that elusive indicator of customer demand. By studying the market, managers can determine what customers crave, and in turn, decide what products to produce, how many to produce, and where to produce them. It's a delicate balancing act, keeping in mind the customer's satisfaction and demand.

Once the production location is chosen, the focus shifts to scheduling workloads and equipment maintenance - a task that requires precision, as every detail counts. A minor misstep can cost a company dearly in the long run. I recall my days working at retail giants like Wal-Mart and Target, where every aspect of the business, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments, was meticulously planned out in a detailed booklet. Having a clear plan of action ensures that the company runs smoothly, without confusion or misdirection.

Supply, the second key element in the supply chain management equation, involves strategic decisions about a company's core capabilities and outsourcing partnerships. It's a delicate dance of determining which divisions of production are best suited for each process, and when to outsource work to other companies. The goal is to create 'velocity' - the ability to provide quality, flexibility, and low costs. It's a juggling act that requires a manager's deft touch.

A haunting message scrawled on a street corner, a stark reminder of the oppressed. Ellen Page, the talented star of Juno, stands alone, a cardboard sign held high above her head, the bold words "Hitler is alive in Burma" written in Sharpie. Burma, or Myanmar, a Southeast Asian nation ruled by a ruthless military junta that seized power in 1962 through a violent coup d'état. Just a decade ago, in 2007, a series of protests erupted, dubbed the "Saffron Revolution," as thousands of Burmese monks took to the streets, donning their iconic saffron robes. The government, though initially tolerant, soon cracked down, unleashing a brutal crackdown on the peaceful gatherings. Journalists were arrested and foreign reporters, including Japanese photojournalist Kenji Nagai, were killed for simply bearing witness. The official death toll stands at 13, but Colonel Hla Win, a defector from the army, revealed a chilling truth: "The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

This is just a grim snapshot of a timeless tale. The desire to silence dissent and maintain control has been a hallmark of governments throughout history. From ancient Rome, where emperors claimed divine right to rule, to modern-day leaders who seek to crush opposition, this pattern persists. Japanese emperors were considered gods, sent to guide their people towards prosperity, while our own president, George W. Bush, reportedly held clandestine meetings with Ted Haggard, leader of a fundamentalist group. The 1989 Tiananmen Square protests in China, the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, and, of course, the atrocities of the Third Reich all serve as stark reminders of the dangers of unchecked power.

The inimitable legacy of Duke Ellington in the realm of jazz can be largely attributed to his remarkable longevity, which, in turn, allowed him to continually shape and evolve his orchestra. Though his piano playing is often understated in many of his compositions, Ellington's prowess as a composer is undeniable, particularly in his ability to craft rich, complex pieces that showcased the diverse talents of his band members. By carefully crafting the framework for improvisation, as well as writing intricately orchestrated passages that highlighted the unique styles of individual musicians, Ellington created a distinctive sound that was both original and coherent. His deep understanding of each player's voice and how they blended together in the ensemble enabled him to compose some of the most groundbreaking and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music dictionary provides insight into Ellington's innovative approach to sound, citing his use of voice as a "jazz instrument" in Creole Love Call, an early example of his ability to incorporate vocal texture without the constraints of lyrics. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece exemplifies Ellington's skill in complementing the style of his soloists, a characteristic that defines his career. The piece unfolds over six choruses, each with its own distinct character:

Chorus 1: A call-and-response exchange between voice and reeds, where the voice begins with a smooth, melodic tone, gradually shifting to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo that expands on the basic melody, emphasizing several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: A sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, accompanied by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: The full band echoes the first chorus, with a call-and-response exchange between the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus, as the reeds initiate the call-and-response, backed by syncopated stop-time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the first chorus's structure, with call-and-response between voice and reeds. In this final chorus, the voice adopts the growl technique, soloing like an instrument.

Ellington's use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is but one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington masterfully combines his expertise in orchestration with his ear for tone color. The call-and-response phrase between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing is a prime example of Ellington's ability to create a rich, complementary sound by blending vocal and instrumental elements. It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing) further explores these ideas, as Ellington skillfully utilizes Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton's muted trombone to introduce the melody.

It was a nagging void that had plagued her since adolescence - a sense of yearning that she couldn't quite quench. It started when she was 14, right in the midst of navigating the ups and downs of being a teenager. Three years later, at 17, the feeling still lingered, but now she was convinced it was a desire for connection with someone, not just a thing. Yet, despite the attention from a few boys, none of them had truly piqued her interest. She often found herself lost in self-reflection, searching for answers to this enigma. Theories had surfaced over the years, but nothing had ever felt quite right. Life went on, with her constantly questioning her desires, searching for a resolution.

Her home life was typically a serene sanctuary. Her parents were calm and peaceful individuals who rarely argued with each other. Oddly enough, they were even less likely to argue with their daughter, who was always trying to assert her independence and vibrant personality. This dynamic created an interesting contrast between her parents' tranquility and her lively, outgoing nature, making her even more endearing to those around her.

But this particular day was different. As she wandered from room to room, seeking inspiration, she was jolted by a blood-curdling scream from the kitchen. Her mother's melodious voice pierced the air, followed by her frantic words. She rushed into the kitchen, panic setting in as she frantically asked, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" Her mother lay on the ground, writhing in pain, repeatedly muttering "Ow" in short gasps. Her daughter rushed to her side, placing a hand on her to offer support. "Ouch... sweetie, I... need you to take me to... the hospital." The words tumbled out in a rush, and her daughter could sense the gravity of her mother's pain. "Okay, Mom, just show me where to pick you up." Her mother pointed, and in that moment, her daughter was grateful for her fitness classes, which had prepared her to take on this unexpected role. She gently lifted her mother and drove her to the hospital.

The hospital's sterile atmosphere, heavy with the scent of disinfectant and illness, was a daunting place. But her daughter's focus was solely on helping her mother. She swiftly carried her in and called for the doctors, who quickly arrived to assess the situation. A few worried faces gathered around as they rushed her mother onto a rolling bed. The medical team whisked her away, leaving her daughter to sit anxiously, her mind racing with concern.

It turned out her mother had taken a tumble off a stool while trying to retrieve a vase from a high cabinet.

The purpose of this study was to demonstrate the benefits of adhering to the Mediterranean Diet (Med diet), as measured by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," in reducing the risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a variation of the Med diet that emphasizes higher consumption of plant foods, including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes, while limiting saturated fats and animal products, with moderate alcohol intake allowed.

Previous studies have shown a connection between adherence to the Med diet and a lower risk of total and cardiovascular mortality, and an intervention trial found the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and improving cholesterol ratios in obese individuals. However, these studies did not specifically examine the relationship between the Med diet and stroke or stroke mortality.

This study, which followed 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, free of heart disease or diabetes, utilized data from the Nurses' Health Study, a comprehensive cohort study of 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Over six intervals between 1984 and 2004, researchers calculated an aMed diet score based on self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs), which assessed nutrient intake over a one-year period. Remarkably, over 95% of participants continued their participation throughout the 20-year study.

To validate the accuracy of FFQs, each report of heart disease, fatal heart disease, and stroke was cross-checked against medical records, hospital records, autopsy reports, or death certificates. In cases where records were unavailable, "probable" cases were included, accounting for approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts.

To mitigate the impact of individual fluctuations and better represent long-term dietary habits, cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from two preceding years). The researchers also controlled for potential confounding factors, such as age, smoking status, body mass index, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Using Cox proportional-hazard modeling, the study found that a higher aMed diet score was associated with a reduced risk of heart disease and stroke in women. Over the course of 20 years, a total of 2,391 incident CHD cases, 1,763 incident strokes, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were documented. Women in the top aMed quintile exhibited a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

We're still reeling from the economic earthquake that shook the United States to its core in 2007. Unemployment skyrocketed, the housing market imploded, and some of America's top corporations crumbled to the ground. And here we are, still grappling with the wreckage – so it's only natural to wonder: how did this catastrophe unfold, and can we prevent it from happening again? In a nutshell, the financial crisis was triggered by shortsighted and reckless government policies that pushed banks and financial institutions to hand out subprime loans to those who couldn't afford them, against the backdrop of a fragile and underprepared financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) got saddled with underwriting and repackaging these dodgy mortgages into CDOs and CDSs, which had disastrous consequences when borrowers defaulted on their payments.

The roots of the financial crisis stretch back to 1999, when President Clinton was on a mission to secure a second term. He sought to boost his popularity by easing lending regulations, setting the stage for the subprime crisis that would unfold seven years later. As Steven Holmes of the New York Times astutely observed in 1999, Fannie Mae – the country's largest underwriter of home mortgages – was feeling the heat from the Clinton administration to make more loans to low- and moderate-income borrowers, while also being pressed by shareholders to maintain its impressive profit growth. Holmes prophetically warned of the potential consequences: "But the government-subsidized corporation may struggle in an economic downturn, prompting a government bailout similar to the one for the savings and loan industry in the 1980s." As we now know, poorly advised lending would lead to an economic meltdown.

A perfect storm of factors contributed to the economic freefall, including the proliferation of innovative but complicated mortgage products like adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs). These complex financial instruments entwined the housing market with other sectors of the economy, leaving U.S. households and financial markets perilously exposed to even slight changes in housing prices. And then, as if on cue, the housing bubble burst, leaving financial institutions that had invested in mortgage-backed securities reeling. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively held $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007 – a staggering 30% of the country's GDP. In the aftermath, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at fire-sale prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to convert to commercial banks subject to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie, meanwhile, were left with a whopping $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were taken under government control in September 2008.

The thrill of exposition - that moment when writers stretch their wings and soar, leaving readers in awe of their prose.  Or, more often, the part where readers' eyelids droop and they hastily click the "Back" button, muttering a curse under their breath.  Dr. Merlin has been known to pound her keyboard in frustration when she finds herself stuck in a quagmire of unnecessary details, and it's not the fun kind of frustration.

Exposition is not a friend to writers.

Even seasoned writers like Dr. Merlin still fall prey to long, meandering passages that leave nothing but a sense of tedium in their wake.  We know the essential writing tip: "Show, don't tell," but it's a hard habit to break.  Exposition is that pesky voice in our heads that whispers, "Get the backstory over with so we can get to the good stuff" (not to be confused with the voice that urges us to reveal every intimate detail of our characters' pasts).

So, what is exposition? It's the act of telling the reader what's happened, usually in straightforward language.  In film, it's the scene where one character dumps a load of information on another (think "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner").  In fiction, it's the author doing the telling.

Let's take a look at an example.  Imagine a story where the heroine meets her beloved, gets married in a grand ceremony, and her husband is brutally murdered before her eyes.  You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to unfold over two pages, with both characters only uttering a few words.  You'd want to see more of the husband's character come alive through his words and actions, and the heroine's transformation as she falls in love with him.  You'd want to feel the depth of their bond, the impact his presence has on her life, and the clues that hint at her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams.  By doing this, you'd become invested in his fate and hers, and mourn his loss alongside her.  That's what makes a story come alive - the meat on the bone of the plot: "They met, they married, he died."

As writers, we need to provide that meat.  Sometimes it's tempting to rush past certain details, but the payoff is worth the extra effort.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and know he used to be in the Air Force, now works the night shift at a gas station, has been married twice, has no kids, and dreams of owning the gas station someday.  Don't just give the reader a laundry list of facts - show us through his actions, dialogue, and expressions why these details matter.  Give your readers a reason to care about this character and the world you're creating.

I tuned in to the local news from Columbus, Ohio, and witnessed two newscasts, one on August 13, 2011. The first one, NBC 4's live broadcast in the morning, caught my attention with a particularly disturbing story. A man named Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio, had allegedly stabbed his wife, though her name was not mentioned. His mug shot was displayed, and he looked every inch the embodiment of malevolence. Not surprisingly, this developing story received only two minutes of airtime. I think they devoted an adequate amount of time to the story, considering its gravity.

The second story told the heart-wrenching tale of an 18-year-old named Travis Buyers, who was shot in the Sharon Woods area. He was left critically injured, and at the time, no arrests had been made or suspects identified. The SWAT Team was hot on the case. I couldn't help but feel that this story received short shrift, and I suspect the reason might be rooted in the fact that the victim was a young black man from a predominantly black neighborhood. I've observed this phenomenon before – minorities are often overlooked when they're victims of crime. In contrast, when a white child or adult falls victim, the media sensationalizes the story, whereas a minority victim is lucky to receive minimal coverage. 

Subsequent stories included an investigation into a gunshot hole found on a Med-Flight helicopter. Details were provided about the possible location of the incident, and it was determined that a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle was responsible. Crime-Stoppers offered a substantial reward, $5,000, for any information leading to the arrest of the perpetrator.

The forecast for the weekend mentioned rain and thunderstorms on Saturday afternoon, with temperatures expected to hover in the mid-to-low eighties. The segment was brief, but I suspect the anchor wanted to use it as a teaser to keep viewers tuned in.

Another story highlighted the robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. The perpetrator, described as a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie sweatshirt, was allegedly around six feet tall and weighed around 150 pounds. I found it striking that they devoted an inordinate amount of time to emphasizing the robber's skin tone and the darkness of his complexion.

Lastly, a story reported on Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas-based marijuana kingpin who had been sentenced to 300 months in prison for conspiring to distribute large quantities of marijuana to Ohio from Texas. I couldn't help but notice that they chose to mention his Hispanic heritage, which seemed irrelevant to the story. It left me wondering if they thought it added a layer of gravity to the narrative or if it was simply a gratuitous detail.

There's an unbreakable bond between brothers, a connection that runs deeper than words can express. This bond is a complex web of emotions - love, pride, jealousy, and even cruelty - all intertwined like the threads of a rich tapestry. Brothers have a unique understanding of each other, one that transcends the boundaries of ordinary relationships. When the chips are down and things get tough, the true nature of this bond is revealed, whether it's beautiful or ugly. The cost of this bond is steep, and it's only when we confront the consequences of our actions that we can truly understand its power. When we look at our brother and see our own reflection staring back, we're forced to confront the truth about ourselves - our flaws, our strengths, and our true character. This is a theme that's expertly woven throughout William Faulkner's "The Scarlet Ibis", a haunting tale of two brothers locked in a dance of emotions. Set against the backdrop of a lush, vivid landscape, their journey is a futile yet poignant one, marked by the bitter clash of disappointment and pride. Ultimately, only one brother emerges unscathed, leaving the other to grapple with the devastating consequences of their actions.

At the heart of this story is the protagonist's all-consuming pride. From the moment he and his little brother, Doodle, set out together, he's driven by a sense of resentment towards the younger boy. He'd envisioned a brother who could share in his adventures, who could keep up with his wild spirit and thirst for excitement. But Doodle's fragile health dashes those hopes, leaving the protagonist feeling frustrated and angry. He's even shown to harbor a dark secret - a desire to eliminate the perceived burden that Doodle represents. Yet, in a subtle yet telling moment, his defenses crumble when he catches Doodle's smile. This fleeting glimpse of joy humanizes the protagonist, revealing a love for his brother that's been there all along. It's a love that's not always easy to acknowledge, but it's a love that ultimately redeems him.

Through the protagonist's actions and interactions with Doodle, Faulkner masterfully explores the complexities of brotherly love and the consequences that come with it. The narrator's perspective adds another layer of depth to the story, offering a glimpse into the protagonist's inner world and the emotions that drive him. As we follow the brothers on their fateful journey, we're forced to confront the darker aspects of human nature - our own flaws, our own capacity for cruelty and love. In the end, it's a powerful reminder that the bonds we form with others are the greatest teachers of all, and that it's only by confronting our own reflections that we can truly grow and change.

I've often found myself wondering about the intricate workings of the human brain, a complex information-processing system that's as baffling as it is fascinating. Over time, our understanding of the brain has evolved, much like the technology that's revolutionized our lives. We've likened it to a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and more recently, to a computer. While these metaphors have been helpful in describing the brain's functions, they also have their limitations, often leading us down a path of misconceptions.

The journey of information processing begins with the sensory organs, which convert physical stimuli like touch, heat, and light into electrical signals. This process is a series of transformations, where the brain's algorithms work their magic, both bottom-up and top-down. For instance, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing assembles basic information like color, orientation, and object borders to determine that you're seeing a box. Meanwhile, top-down processing uses the decisions made earlier to expedite your recognition of the box, perhaps helping you identify it as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole.

As information is processed to some extent, an attention filter decides its importance and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name in a noisy room. This process of processing and filtering is repeated at multiple stages, with attention modulating the results each time.
